Tangents are drawn from $(1,3)$ to the parabola $y^2 = 4x,$ at $A$ and $B.$  Find the length $AB.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.4 cm);

real upperparab (real x) {
  return (sqrt(4*x));
}

real lowerparab (real x) {
  return (-sqrt(4*x));
}

pair A, B, P;

P = (1,3);
A = ((7 + 3*sqrt(5))/2, upperparab((7 + 3*sqrt(5))/2));
B = ((7 - 3*sqrt(5))/2, upperparab((7 - 3*sqrt(5))/2));

draw(graph(upperparab,0,10));
draw(graph(lowerparab,0,10));
draw(interp(A,P,-0.8)--interp(A,P,1.2));
draw(interp(B,P,-1)--interp(B,P,1.5));

dot("$A$", A, N);
dot("$B$", B, W);
dot("$(1,3)$", P, NW);
[/asy]

inference:
Let the equation of the tangent line from $(1,3)$ to the parabola $y^2 = 4x$ be $y = mx + b.$  Then substituting into the equation of the parabola, we get
\[(mx + b)^2 = 4x.\]This simplifies to $m^2 x^2 + 2(mb - 2) x + b^2 = 0.$  Since the tangent line intersects the parabola at only one point, this quadratic must have a double root.  Hence, the discriminant is 0:
\[[2(mb - 2)]^2 - 4m^2 b^2 = 0.\]This simplifies to $16 - 16mb = 0,$ so $mb = 1.$

