B = ((7 - 3*sqrt(5))/2, upperparab((7 - 3*sqrt(5))/2));

draw(graph(upperparab,0,10));
draw(graph(lowerparab,0,10));
draw(interp(A,P,-0.8)--interp(A,P,1.2));
draw(interp(B,P,-1)--interp(B,P,1.5));

dot("$A$", A, N);
dot("$B$", B, W);
dot("$(1,3)$", P, NW);

label("$y = mx + b$", (8,24), E);
[/asy]

Also, since the tangent line passes through $(1,3),$ $3 = m + b.$  Solving, we find $m = \frac{1}{3}$ and $b = \frac{8}{3}.$  Thus, the equation of the tangent line is $y = \frac{1}{3} x + \frac{8}{3}.$

Let $A = (x_1,y_1)$ and $B = (x_2,y_2).$  Then $y_1^2 = 4x_1$ and $y_2^2 = 4x_2,$ so
\[y_1^2 - y_2^2 = 4(x_1 - x_2).\]Also, $y_1 = \frac{1}{3} x_1 + \frac{8}{3}$ and $y_2 = \frac{1}{3} x_2 + \frac{8}{3},$ so
\[y_1 - y_2 = \frac{1}{3} (x_1 - x_2).\]Then
\[\frac{y_1^2 - y_2^2}{y_1 - y_2} = 12.\]This simplifies to $y_1 + y_2 = 12.$

By the distance formula,
\begin{align*}
AB^2 &= (x_1 - x_2)^2 + (y_1 - y_2)^2 \\
&= (x_1 - x_2)^2 + \frac{1}{9} (x_1 - x_2)^2 \\
&= \frac{10}{9} (x_1 - x_2)^2.
\end{align*}Since $y_1^2 = 4x_1$ and $y_2^2 = 4x_2,$
\[x_1 - x_2 = \frac{1}{4} (y_1^2 - y_2^2) = \frac{1}{4} (y_1 + y_2)(y_1 - y_2) = 3(y_1 - y_2).\]Then
\[AB^2 = \frac{10}{9} \cdot 9(y_1 - y_2)^2 = 10(y_1 - y_2)^2 = 10 \cdot \frac{1}{9} (x_1 - x_2)^2 = \frac{10}{9} (x_1 - x_2)^2.\]Also,
\[(y_1 - y_2)^2 = \frac{1}{9} (x_1 - x_2)^2,\]so $(x_1 - x_2)^2 = 9(y_1 - y_2)^2.$  Then
\[AB^2 = 10(y_1 - y_2)^2 = \frac{10}{9} (x_1 - x_2)^2 = \frac{10}{9} \cdot 9(y_1 - y_2)^2 = 10(y_1 - y_2)^2.\]Hence, $AB = \sqrt{10} |y_1 - y_2|.$

Since $y_1 + y_2 = 12,$ $y_1 - y_2 = \frac{y_1^2 - y_2^2}{y_1 + y_2} = \frac{4(x_1 - x_2)}{12} = \frac{1}{3} (x_1 - x_2).$  Then
\[AB = \sqrt{10} \cdot \frac{1}{3} |x_1 - x_2|.\]Since $y_1 = \frac{1}{3} x_1 + \frac{8}{3}$ and $y_2 = \frac{1}{3} x_2 + \frac{8}{3},$
\[y_1 - y_2 = \frac{1}{3} (x_1 - x_2).\]Then
\[AB = \sqrt{10} |y_1 - y_2| = \sqrt{10} \cdot \frac{1}{3} |x_1 - x_2| = \sqrt{10} |y_1 - y_2| = \boxed{\sqrt{10}}.\]

